But it was fusion-period dramedy Hong Gil-dong in 2008 that changed how the industry perceived Sung as an actress.

That same year, she also appeared in her first big-screen starring role as a Korean-American adoptee who returns to her native country to search for her biological mother in Maybe (titled Rabbit and Lizard in Korean).
In 2011, Sung left SidusHQ and transferred to King Kong Entertainment.
A more traditional melodrama followed with Feast of the Gods (2012), about two rival female chefs of Korean royal court cuisine.
In 2013, she played a genius with psychogenic amnesia in The Secret of Birth.
Later that year, she replaced Han Hye-jin as one of the hosts of talk show Healing Camp, Aren't You Happy.
When Sung's contract with King Kong Entertainment expired in January 2014, she signed with Fantagio.
Sung next played a diva actress who unexpectedly falls for her loyal manager in the 2015 omnibus Summer Snow.

On April 20, 2015, Sung signed an exclusive contract with SL Entertainment.
Sung married golfer Ahn Sung-hyun in May 2017 in a low-key private ceremony.
They had been dating for four years and did not publicly announce their marriage until after the ceremony.
On July 16, 2021, Sung announced on her Instagram that she is pregnant with twins.
Later on January 8, 2022, Sung's agency announced that Sung had given birth to twin daughters on January 7, 2022.
